04356nam a22005655i 9780822393726DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223937267 a10.1515/97808223937262doi  a(DE-B1597)552948  a(OCoLC)761742646  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aP96.W62bM57 2011 7aART0090002bisacsh04a302.2/222231 aMirzoeff, Nicholas, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Right to Look :bA Counterhistory of Visuality /cNicholas Mirzoeff. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b75 illustrations (incl. 11 in color), 2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tPreface. Ineluctable Visualities -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. The Right to Look, or, How to Think With and Against Visuality -- tVisualizing Visuality -- tOne. Oversight: The Ordering of Slavery -- tTwo. The Modern Imaginary: Antislavery Revolutions and the Right to Existence -- tPuerto Rican Counterpoint I -- tThree. Visuality: Authority and War -- tFour. Abolition Realism: Reality, Realisms, and Revolution -- tPuerto Rican Counterpoint II -- tFive. Imperial Visuality and Countervisuality, Ancient and Modern -- tSix. Antifascist Neorealisms: North- South and the Permanent Battle for Algiers -- tMexican- Spanish Counterpoint -- tSeven. Global Counterinsurgency and the Crisis of Visuality -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn The Right to Look, Nicholas Mirzoeff develops a comparative decolonial framework for visual culture studies, the field that he helped to create and shape. Casting modernity as an ongoing contest between visuality and countervisuality, or “the right to look,” he explains how visuality sutures authority to power and renders the association natural. An early-nineteenth-century concept, meaning the visualization of history, visuality has been central to the legitimization of Western hegemony. Mirzoeff identifies three “complexes of visuality”—plantation slavery, imperialism, and the present-day military-industrial complex—and explains how, within each, power is made to seem self-evident through techniques of classification, separation, and aestheticization. At the same time, he shows how each complex of visuality has been countered—by the enslaved, the colonized, and opponents of war, all of whom assert autonomy from authority by claiming the right to look. Encompassing the Caribbean plantation and the Haitian revolution, anticolonialism in the South Pacific, antifascism in Italy and Algeria, and the contemporary global counterinsurgency, The Right to Look is a work of astonishing geographic, temporal, and conceptual reach.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCommunication and culturexPolitical aspects. 0aMass media and world politics. 0aMass mediaxPolitical aspects. 0aVisual communicationxPolitical aspects. 7aART / Criticism.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822393726zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822393726423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822393726/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles